### Describe the problem that you experienced

The docs are stating that `toObservable` _may_ emit the first value synchronously, but it doesn't state under what conditions. In my experience and from checking the code, it seems values are _always_ emitted asynchronously.

I verified this both in a component and a root service, because of the different timing of component and root effects.

**Docs**
https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/6789c7ef947952551d7598fe37a3d86093b75720/adev/src/content/ecosystem/rxjs-interop/signals-interop.md?plain=1#L93

**toObservable source code**
https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/6789c7ef947952551d7598fe37a3d86093b75720/packages/core/rxjs-interop/src/to_observable.ts#L45-L70

**Example**
```TypeScript
const mySignal = signal('myValue');
const myObservable = toObservable(mySignal);

console.log('preSubscribe');
myObservable.subscribe(console.log);
console.log('postSubscribe');

// output:
// preSubscribe
// postSubscribe
// myValue
```

### Enter the URL of the topic with the problem

https://angular.dev/ecosystem/rxjs-interop#timing-of-toobservable

### Describe what you want to experience that would fix the problem

I would suggest to either specify more precisely under which conditions the first emission is synchronous or remove that part in the docs.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

At the moment, the declaration of the `effect()` function is as follows:
```typescript
export declare function effect(effectFn: (onCleanup: EffectCleanupRegisterFn) => void, options?: CreateEffectOptions): EffectRef;
```

In my use case, I want Angulars `router.navigate` to run inside of an effect to reflect the change of some value in the URL.
However `navigate()` returns a `Promise` which does not work with the `effect()` which only allows `void`.

```typescript
effect(async () => {
    const myParam = this.someSignal();

    await _router.navigate([], {
        queryParams: { foo: myParam },
        queryParamsHandling: "merge",
    });
});
```

### Proposed solution

Since the example is working, just merely seems to be an Issue on the declaration of the `effect()` function.

My proposal is to change the definition as follows:
```typescript
export declare function effect(effectFn: (onCleanup: EffectCleanupRegisterFn) => void | Promise, options?: CreateEffectOptions): EffectRef;
```

### Alternatives considered

This is coming from [@typescript-eslint.io/rules/no-misused-promises/](https://typescript-eslint.io/rules/no-misused-promises/) and could be disabled but this would harm the rest of the codebase.

This update improves the handling of inlined critical CSS to align with `autoCsp`, ensuring compliance with Content Security Policy (CSP) directives. Previously, inlined styles could trigger CSP violations in certain configurations. With this fix, critical CSS is inlined in a way that maintains security while supporting `autoCsp`.  

Closes #29603

